1
00:00:21,855 --> 00:00:29,855
♪

2
00:01:23,083 --> 00:01:26,587
(chanting)

3
00:01:26,878 --> 00:01:34,878
♪

4
00:01:48,942 --> 00:01:51,153
(cheering)

5
00:01:51,445 --> 00:01:59,445
♪

6
00:02:19,014 --> 00:02:20,432
Everyone have fun!

7
00:02:20,724 --> 00:02:22,142
♪

8
00:02:22,434 --> 00:02:23,434
Here we go!

9
00:02:23,560 --> 00:02:25,812
(cheering)

10
00:02:26,104 --> 00:02:34,104
♪

11
00:02:36,031 --> 00:02:39,493
(chanting)

12
00:02:39,785 --> 00:02:42,162
♪

13
00:02:42,454 --> 00:02:44,665
(cheering)

14
00:02:44,956 --> 00:02:52,956
♪

15
00:03:06,061 --> 00:03:14,061
♪

16
00:04:38,153 --> 00:04:39,488
Hello.

17
00:04:44,159 --> 00:04:46,661
Kids! Come here.

18
00:04:48,538 --> 00:04:52,250
Learning to play music isn't just
holding the instrument and playing.

19
00:04:52,542 --> 00:04:58,131
You have to practice certain
exercises, and learn to read music.

20
00:04:58,423 --> 00:05:03,011
I arrived in Cateura in 2006 to
work as an environmental technician.

21
00:05:03,303 --> 00:05:05,869
My job was to work
with families that collect

22
00:05:05,881 --> 00:05:08,058
recyclable materials
from the landfill

23
00:05:08,350 --> 00:05:11,520
and sell them as
their source of income.

24
00:05:11,812 --> 00:05:13,772
They are known as gancheros.

25
00:05:20,570 --> 00:05:21,947
♪

26
00:05:22,239 --> 00:05:28,703
My job was to educate them about
better ways to collect and sort garbage.

27
00:05:28,995 --> 00:05:32,249
♪

28
00:05:32,541 --> 00:05:35,919
As I began to better understand
the situation of families in Cateura,

29
00:05:36,211 --> 00:05:38,897
I realized that the
future of most kids is

30
00:05:38,909 --> 00:05:41,800
to work with garbage
just like their parents.

31
00:05:42,092 --> 00:05:45,262
♪

32
00:05:45,554 --> 00:05:50,350
Here in Paraguay, the social conditions
often limit the ability to dream.

33
00:05:50,642 --> 00:05:53,812
If you're born in the wrong place,
you don't have the right to dream.

34
00:05:54,104 --> 00:05:57,858
♪

35
00:05:58,149 --> 00:06:00,360
(demonstrating rhythm)

36
00:06:00,652 --> 00:06:01,945
Count with me.

37
00:06:02,237 --> 00:06:06,783
♪

38
00:06:07,075 --> 00:06:12,163
When I was young, music was the first
thing that gave me a sense of purpose.

39
00:06:12,455 --> 00:06:14,791
(rhythmic clapping)

40
00:06:16,960 --> 00:06:21,965
Thus, I decided to teach music
to the children of the gancheros.

41
00:06:22,257 --> 00:06:26,553
Follow my count.
Your mind is wandering.

42
00:06:26,845 --> 00:06:29,139
When I started to offer
music classes in Cateura,

43
00:06:29,431 --> 00:06:33,226
the news that I was offering free
music classes spread very quickly.

44
00:06:33,518 --> 00:06:34,978
And many kids showed up.

45
00:06:35,270 --> 00:06:37,188
More kids than instruments.

46
00:06:37,480 --> 00:06:40,483
(rhythmic clapping)

47
00:06:40,775 --> 00:06:45,363
We did have a few instruments
that people had donated.

48
00:06:45,655 --> 00:06:51,369
But we didn't have enough instruments
for all of the kids that wanted to learn.

49
00:06:51,661 --> 00:06:54,456
(demonstrating rhythm)

50
00:06:54,748 --> 00:06:58,501
And I said to myself, "We have to do
something to get more instruments."

51
00:06:59,794 --> 00:07:01,212
(demonstrating rhythm)

52
00:07:01,504 --> 00:07:04,299
♪

53
00:07:04,591 --> 00:07:07,391
However, a community like Cateura
is not a safe place to have a violin.

54
00:07:07,677 --> 00:07:08,803
♪

55
00:07:09,095 --> 00:07:11,681
In fact, a violin is worth
more than a house.

56
00:07:11,973 --> 00:07:18,104
♪

57
00:07:18,396 --> 00:07:21,399
I met Colá when he was working
in the landfill as a ganchero.

58
00:07:21,691 --> 00:07:25,028
♪

59
00:07:25,320 --> 00:07:29,574
Colá saw that I was teaching music
and one day he approached me.

60
00:07:29,866 --> 00:07:34,037
He told me that he had
experience working in carpentry.

61
00:07:34,329 --> 00:07:37,290
♪

62
00:07:37,582 --> 00:07:41,962
Favio asked me, " Do you think we
can make instruments from garbage?"

63
00:07:42,253 --> 00:07:44,130
So I thought about
the idea for a while.

64
00:07:44,422 --> 00:07:48,134
And then Favio brought me a real violin
to see if I could make something similar.

65
00:07:48,426 --> 00:07:52,263
I took all the measurements
and went to look for a metal can.

66
00:07:52,555 --> 00:07:55,115
And I told him, "That's what
I'm going to use to make a violin."

67
00:07:55,266 --> 00:08:03,266
♪

68
00:08:05,735 --> 00:08:09,698
It was a continuous
process of trial and error.

69
00:08:09,990 --> 00:08:17,990
♪

70
00:08:20,375 --> 00:08:24,504
I asked myself if it was something
that could be used to play music

71
00:08:24,796 --> 00:08:26,232
or if it would be
completely useless.

72
00:08:26,256 --> 00:08:34,256
♪

73
00:08:48,987 --> 00:08:51,197
(plucking violin)

74
00:08:51,489 --> 00:08:54,826
♪

75
00:08:55,118 --> 00:08:57,328
(playing violin)

76
00:08:57,620 --> 00:09:05,620
♪

77
00:09:09,466 --> 00:09:14,763
When I played the first violin, it
was a moment of enlightenment

78
00:09:15,055 --> 00:09:20,477
because we realized that it could
function as a real musical instrument.

79
00:09:21,853 --> 00:09:26,024
Then we figured we could
make other types of instruments.

80
00:09:26,316 --> 00:09:27,316
♪

81
00:09:27,400 --> 00:09:29,569
I could use this to make a drum.

82
00:09:29,861 --> 00:09:36,493
♪

83
00:09:36,785 --> 00:09:42,373
This drum has an
X-ray for a drum head.

84
00:09:42,665 --> 00:09:45,293
♪

85
00:09:45,585 --> 00:09:49,839
I can use this to make a cello.

86
00:09:50,131 --> 00:09:56,179
This weird-looking cello
is made from an oil can,

87
00:09:56,471 --> 00:10:02,018
as well as a wooden
spoon used for cooking.

88
00:10:02,310 --> 00:10:06,272
The tuning pegs are
made from wooden spoons,

89
00:10:06,564 --> 00:10:08,817
a water spigot,

90
00:10:09,109 --> 00:10:12,445
and a size 12 heel
from a women's shoe.

91
00:10:12,737 --> 00:10:20,737
Two nice pieces of wood from a palette that
I can use for a cello, bass, or violin.

92
00:10:21,329 --> 00:10:29,329
♪

93
00:10:33,091 --> 00:10:37,220
No one believed that we could make
musical instruments from garbage.

94
00:10:37,512 --> 00:10:39,055
♪

95
00:10:39,347 --> 00:10:41,474
But in the end,
we made them all.

96
00:10:41,766 --> 00:10:44,894
♪

97
00:10:49,899 --> 00:10:55,613
♪

98
00:10:55,905 --> 00:10:57,265
Play using the
top end of the bow.

99
00:10:57,490 --> 00:11:05,490
♪

100
00:11:09,252 --> 00:11:13,047
Today is the first day you're playing
this song. You're going to make mistakes.

101
00:11:13,339 --> 00:11:16,551
But don't let that
upset you. Alright?

102
00:11:16,843 --> 00:11:19,280
You have to keep trying until
you get it. Alright, let's start again.

103
00:11:19,304 --> 00:11:24,684
♪

104
00:11:24,976 --> 00:11:28,521
In the beginning, I
felt really frustrated

105
00:11:28,813 --> 00:11:32,150
because nothing I played
sounded as good as I wanted it to.

106
00:11:32,442 --> 00:11:33,442
♪

107
00:11:33,693 --> 00:11:36,029
Hold on a second.

108
00:11:36,321 --> 00:11:37,321
No.

109
00:11:37,447 --> 00:11:42,410
In a good orchestra, all of
the violins sound the same.

110
00:11:42,702 --> 00:11:45,997
That means you have to
play the same notes in unison.

111
00:11:46,289 --> 00:11:50,877
Your technique is what makes
the instruments sound different.

112
00:11:51,169 --> 00:11:53,755
That's why your
technique is so important.

113
00:11:54,047 --> 00:11:55,965
Let's try it again.

114
00:11:57,592 --> 00:11:59,886
(demonstrating rhythm)

115
00:12:00,178 --> 00:12:08,178
♪

116
00:12:20,990 --> 00:12:26,120
One day, my grandmother saw a
flyer for guitar and violin lessons.

117
00:12:26,412 --> 00:12:28,706
And without asking, she
signed me up for classes.

118
00:12:28,998 --> 00:12:29,998
♪

119
00:12:30,250 --> 00:12:32,877
I used to dream
of being a singer.

120
00:12:33,169 --> 00:12:37,090
I love music, especially rock music. I'm
a fan of the Beatles and similar groups.

121
00:12:37,382 --> 00:12:39,982
I used to think, " How great
would it be to learn to play music."

122
00:12:40,218 --> 00:12:42,905
Before, if you wanted to study music,
you had to pay for classes in Asunción.

123
00:12:42,929 --> 00:12:47,517
♪

124
00:12:47,809 --> 00:12:52,438
But then I found this opportunity for
music lessons with recycled instruments.

125
00:12:52,730 --> 00:12:56,442
I never imagined that it would
be free. Especially nowadays.

126
00:12:56,734 --> 00:13:00,738
♪

127
00:13:01,030 --> 00:13:03,491
I live with my dad...

128
00:13:03,783 --> 00:13:05,201
with my mom...

129
00:13:05,493 --> 00:13:07,453
with my sister,
and with our pets.

130
00:13:07,745 --> 00:13:14,836
♪

131
00:13:15,128 --> 00:13:16,546
You have to cut
all of the knots.

132
00:13:16,838 --> 00:13:18,506
Otherwise it's
hard to work with.

133
00:13:18,798 --> 00:13:26,798
I worked as a ganchero in the landfill
for two years from the age of 16 to 18.

134
00:13:27,890 --> 00:13:28,975
♪

135
00:13:29,267 --> 00:13:35,189
In the landfill, I was fortunate to
find lots of different cassette tapes.

136
00:13:35,481 --> 00:13:37,608
One of the best tapes I found

137
00:13:37,900 --> 00:13:39,694
was an album by Phil Collins.

138
00:13:39,986 --> 00:13:42,864
His music was a huge
part of my life back then.

139
00:13:43,156 --> 00:13:49,954
After that, I started to learn about other
music that I didn't even know existed.

140
00:13:50,246 --> 00:13:53,583
Those groups included Led
Zeppelin and Black Sabbath.

141
00:13:53,875 --> 00:13:57,462
This is one of the most important
things that I've taught my daughters.

142
00:13:58,880 --> 00:14:01,632
Musicians from
all over the world.

143
00:14:01,924 --> 00:14:05,595
I have always been interested
in the three great composers.

144
00:14:05,887 --> 00:14:06,971
Mozart,

145
00:14:07,263 --> 00:14:08,431
Sebastian Bach,

146
00:14:08,723 --> 00:14:10,433
Ludwig van Beethoven.

147
00:14:12,935 --> 00:14:16,022
Jimmy Hendrix. Sex Pistols.
Who has never heard of them?

148
00:14:18,608 --> 00:14:26,608
All my life I tried to be part of a
band, or have an instrument to play.

149
00:14:27,700 --> 00:14:29,285
But I never had
that opportunity.

150
00:14:34,165 --> 00:14:35,166
Bye, mom.

151
00:14:35,458 --> 00:14:37,085
♪

152
00:14:37,377 --> 00:14:40,630
My closest friends
are the violinists.

153
00:14:40,922 --> 00:14:42,507
Which are María...

154
00:14:42,799 --> 00:14:44,342
♪

155
00:14:44,634 --> 00:14:45,635
Natalia...

156
00:14:45,927 --> 00:14:47,553
♪

157
00:14:47,845 --> 00:14:49,639
And Tania.

158
00:14:49,931 --> 00:14:54,394
♪

159
00:14:54,685 --> 00:14:58,773
My most precious
possession is my violin.

160
00:14:59,065 --> 00:15:00,066
♪

161
00:15:00,358 --> 00:15:02,276
I treat it like a jewel.

162
00:15:02,568 --> 00:15:03,653
♪

163
00:15:03,945 --> 00:15:09,283
I have other beautiful things like
bracelets, rings, and necklaces.

164
00:15:09,575 --> 00:15:11,735
But I'm starting to pay less
attention to those things.

165
00:15:11,994 --> 00:15:13,496
Now I'm focusing
more on my violin.

166
00:15:13,788 --> 00:15:14,788
♪

167
00:15:14,956 --> 00:15:18,209
Hey guys. How are
you? Go on inside.

168
00:15:18,501 --> 00:15:21,421
- Hey, how are you Jorge?
- Spectacular.

169
00:15:21,712 --> 00:15:23,107
Can I have your
attention for a moment?

170
00:15:23,131 --> 00:15:27,802
Someone heard about our orchestra
and has invited us to play at an event.

171
00:15:28,094 --> 00:15:30,596
That means we have only a few
days until our first performance.

172
00:15:30,888 --> 00:15:34,350
The piece of music that we
will be playing is "Ode to Joy."

173
00:15:34,642 --> 00:15:39,063
Because it's the piece of music
they want to hear that night.

174
00:15:39,355 --> 00:15:43,526
And the main part of the song
will be played by the first violins.

175
00:15:46,320 --> 00:15:54,320
♪

176
00:15:54,704 --> 00:15:56,372
Try it again.

177
00:15:56,664 --> 00:16:04,664
♪

178
00:16:24,108 --> 00:16:26,360
Much better.

179
00:16:26,652 --> 00:16:28,446
Everyone in the group is unique.

180
00:16:29,780 --> 00:16:33,659
Some of us learn the
music faster than others.

181
00:16:33,951 --> 00:16:36,751
Some of you are very focused, but
others have trouble paying attention.

182
00:16:36,787 --> 00:16:38,873
Those are the
dynamics of a group. Ok?

183
00:16:40,166 --> 00:16:46,756
So we have to help those who have
trouble focusing and learning. Understand?

184
00:16:47,048 --> 00:16:48,966
You must stay focused.

185
00:16:49,258 --> 00:16:51,761
One ice cream
cone each. Just one.

186
00:16:54,555 --> 00:16:57,767
Hold on to that. There you go.

187
00:16:58,893 --> 00:17:02,688
Why did you fool me?

188
00:17:02,980 --> 00:17:08,152
The melancholy
is going to kill me.

189
00:17:08,444 --> 00:17:14,659
And now, without
you, my life is over...

190
00:17:14,951 --> 00:17:19,789
(singing a round)

191
00:17:40,476 --> 00:17:42,895
(radio playing)

192
00:17:48,067 --> 00:17:50,486
(dog barking)

193
00:18:14,927 --> 00:18:17,346
(clapping)

194
00:18:24,604 --> 00:18:26,647
All done? Nice work, María.

195
00:18:26,939 --> 00:18:28,219
- Do you like how it looks?
- No.

196
00:18:28,357 --> 00:18:36,357
♪

197
00:18:49,712 --> 00:18:51,112
Who put the
strings on this violin?

198
00:18:51,297 --> 00:18:53,633
♪

199
00:18:53,924 --> 00:18:55,217
The strings are on backwards.

200
00:18:55,509 --> 00:18:57,094
♪

201
00:18:57,386 --> 00:18:59,972
Our instruments are out of
tune. We need to tune them again.

202
00:19:00,264 --> 00:19:01,349
♪

203
00:19:01,641 --> 00:19:04,977
Are you sure you have the
correct piece of sheet music?

204
00:19:05,269 --> 00:19:07,396
Then what's wrong?

205
00:19:07,688 --> 00:19:08,856
One, two, three and...

206
00:19:09,148 --> 00:19:10,941
(demonstrating music)

207
00:19:11,233 --> 00:19:13,861
No. One more time.
Last time through.

208
00:19:14,153 --> 00:19:15,696
♪

209
00:19:15,988 --> 00:19:18,157
Let's give a round of applause

210
00:19:18,449 --> 00:19:23,454
for director Favio Chávez and the
Recycled Orchestra from Cateura.

211
00:19:23,746 --> 00:19:25,414
For your enjoyment.

212
00:19:25,706 --> 00:19:33,706
♪

213
00:20:16,966 --> 00:20:19,301
(applause)

214
00:20:21,554 --> 00:20:27,351
♪

215
00:20:27,643 --> 00:20:30,312
Just to be on stage at this
point is an accomplishment for us.

216
00:20:30,604 --> 00:20:31,897
♪

217
00:20:32,189 --> 00:20:33,649
How well we play is secondary.

218
00:20:33,941 --> 00:20:38,362
♪

219
00:20:38,654 --> 00:20:41,532
The challenge we were faced with

220
00:20:41,824 --> 00:20:45,411
is how to convert our small
orchestra of recycled instruments

221
00:20:45,703 --> 00:20:47,329
into an actual
symphonic orchestra.

222
00:20:47,621 --> 00:20:49,457
♪

223
00:20:49,749 --> 00:20:52,960
We started to think that
we could play music for real.

224
00:20:53,252 --> 00:21:00,760
♪

225
00:21:04,930 --> 00:21:08,017
About 25 years ago, this
creek was clean with white sand.

226
00:21:08,309 --> 00:21:10,895
We used to call it Arroyo
Moroti in the Guaraní language.

227
00:21:11,187 --> 00:21:13,063
That means "white creek."

228
00:21:14,774 --> 00:21:19,028
We used to wash clothes here.
And kids would bathe in the water.

229
00:21:19,320 --> 00:21:20,780
It's a shame.

230
00:21:25,951 --> 00:21:28,662
When my family moved
here, there was just this creek.

231
00:21:28,954 --> 00:21:31,165
There were no gardens.
There was nothing.

232
00:21:31,457 --> 00:21:35,336
We couldn't plant anything because
when it rained, everything would flood.

233
00:21:37,963 --> 00:21:41,634
We have to plant along the
creek to prevent erosion of the soil.

234
00:21:43,010 --> 00:21:47,306
If you don't build up the
riverbank, your house could flood.

235
00:21:47,598 --> 00:21:50,810
When it rains hard, the
water can reach this high.

236
00:21:55,022 --> 00:21:58,901
But thank God it doesn't
flood here anymore.

237
00:21:59,193 --> 00:22:02,905
♪

238
00:22:03,197 --> 00:22:09,537
I'm convinced that the environment
and the deterioration of our surroundings

239
00:22:09,829 --> 00:22:14,041
determines our quality of life.

240
00:22:14,333 --> 00:22:16,213
And I always wanted to
do something about that.

241
00:22:16,252 --> 00:22:18,087
♪

242
00:22:18,379 --> 00:22:24,510
I thought I had the answer to the
problem of dealing with garbage.

243
00:22:24,802 --> 00:22:26,929
But reality taught me otherwise.

244
00:22:27,221 --> 00:22:30,474
♪

245
00:22:30,766 --> 00:22:35,437
The recycling project that brought
me to Cateura in the first place failed.

246
00:22:35,729 --> 00:22:36,939
♪

247
00:22:37,231 --> 00:22:42,486
It failed because you have to change
the entire system beginning at the source.

248
00:22:42,778 --> 00:22:44,572
♪

249
00:22:44,864 --> 00:22:49,118
But my failure, as if by magic,

250
00:22:49,410 --> 00:22:53,581
caused me to persist with
the idea of the orchestra.

251
00:22:53,873 --> 00:23:01,873
♪

252
00:23:23,736 --> 00:23:25,946
(applause and whistling)

253
00:23:26,238 --> 00:23:34,204
♪

254
00:23:40,920 --> 00:23:43,005
♪

255
00:23:43,297 --> 00:23:44,673
Ok. Stop. No, no.

256
00:23:44,965 --> 00:23:45,965
♪

257
00:23:46,050 --> 00:23:47,593
Ok.

258
00:23:47,885 --> 00:23:50,721
Make the notes rounder.

259
00:23:51,013 --> 00:23:56,685
As a group, we have our first
international presentation in 10 days.

260
00:23:58,562 --> 00:24:01,357
♪

261
00:24:01,649 --> 00:24:07,863
We have received an invitation to
perform at the Rio +20 World Summit,

262
00:24:08,155 --> 00:24:11,867
an international conference
related to environmental policy.

263
00:24:12,159 --> 00:24:13,511
We still have a
lot of work to do.

264
00:24:13,535 --> 00:24:16,747
Not just musical improvement
but also emotional preparation.

265
00:24:17,039 --> 00:24:19,291
I don't want to call
anyone out personally.

266
00:24:19,583 --> 00:24:25,005
But preparing for an important event
is not only about learning the music.

267
00:24:26,423 --> 00:24:28,276
You also need to prepare
yourselves personally.

268
00:24:28,300 --> 00:24:31,095
We must develop
proactive attitudes.

269
00:24:31,387 --> 00:24:35,516
Proactive attitudes are the ones
that help accomplish our goals.

270
00:24:35,808 --> 00:24:39,186
So, we need to focus on the actions
that help us achieve positive results.

271
00:24:39,478 --> 00:24:42,648
You all are not like the kids on
the streets, or like any other kid.

272
00:24:42,940 --> 00:24:45,109
Preparing for this trip is
not just about the music.

273
00:24:45,401 --> 00:24:46,401
It's much more than that.

274
00:24:47,444 --> 00:24:51,573
You got it? Help each
other out. We're a team.

275
00:24:51,865 --> 00:24:53,325
Our strength is in our unity.

276
00:24:55,244 --> 00:25:01,250
♪

277
00:25:01,542 --> 00:25:02,835
Play louder.

278
00:25:03,127 --> 00:25:08,424
The violinists have the hardest
job out of the entire group.

279
00:25:08,716 --> 00:25:12,011
They need to have a different
attitude than the others in the group.

280
00:25:12,302 --> 00:25:14,656
When they doubt their abilities,
the instrument doesn't sound good.

281
00:25:14,680 --> 00:25:22,680
♪

282
00:25:23,355 --> 00:25:25,715
They may not feel confident
about the music they're playing,

283
00:25:25,941 --> 00:25:27,794
but they still need to feel
confident about themselves.

284
00:25:27,818 --> 00:25:29,194
Why aren't you playing?

285
00:25:29,486 --> 00:25:31,196
I am playing.

286
00:25:31,488 --> 00:25:34,074
No you're not.
You're not playing.

287
00:25:34,366 --> 00:25:35,806
Let's play through
it one more time.

288
00:25:37,494 --> 00:25:39,580
♪

289
00:25:39,872 --> 00:25:40,872
Oh, no.

290
00:25:41,123 --> 00:25:44,209
Don't be scared to play.

291
00:25:44,501 --> 00:25:46,545
(demonstrates music)

292
00:25:46,837 --> 00:25:49,089
♪

293
00:25:49,381 --> 00:25:51,717
Play without fear.
Don't be afraid to play.

294
00:25:52,009 --> 00:26:00,009
♪

295
00:26:00,851 --> 00:26:07,441
Tania doesn't really have a
father. He is absent from her home.

296
00:26:07,733 --> 00:26:09,068
♪

297
00:26:09,359 --> 00:26:13,113
He abandoned the family. So
she's living with her mother now.

298
00:26:13,405 --> 00:26:14,406
♪

299
00:26:14,698 --> 00:26:20,037
Her mom works all day, so Tania
has to take care of her younger siblings.

300
00:26:20,329 --> 00:26:21,705
♪

301
00:26:21,997 --> 00:26:24,166
She's like the second
mother of the family.

302
00:26:24,458 --> 00:26:26,835
♪

303
00:26:37,346 --> 00:26:41,767
We had a small family problem,
and things weren't so good.

304
00:26:42,059 --> 00:26:47,564
Now I'm living in my aunt's
house. A little distant, but that's all.

305
00:26:47,856 --> 00:26:50,275
I don't see anything
wrong with that.

306
00:26:55,489 --> 00:27:00,953
As a mother, I can tell you that supporting
all of my kids is very difficult.

307
00:27:03,455 --> 00:27:07,209
I'm not always able
to be there for them.

308
00:27:07,501 --> 00:27:12,798
But at least I try to give them advice
about how to take care of themselves.

309
00:27:19,304 --> 00:27:23,308
I used to see Tania walk by my
house, but I didn't know who she was.

310
00:27:28,480 --> 00:27:30,649
Are you going to
take your instrument?

311
00:27:30,941 --> 00:27:31,984
No, it's at the school.

312
00:27:32,276 --> 00:27:33,861
Oh, you have it there.

313
00:27:38,740 --> 00:27:40,325
You look so pretty.

314
00:27:40,617 --> 00:27:41,618
♪

315
00:27:41,910 --> 00:27:46,790
I met Tania the day I
started violin classes.

316
00:27:47,082 --> 00:27:48,082
♪

317
00:27:48,333 --> 00:27:50,419
I was impressed
by how she played.

318
00:27:50,711 --> 00:27:53,881
♪

319
00:27:54,173 --> 00:27:56,758
She inspired me
to play the violin.

320
00:27:57,050 --> 00:27:58,194
I initially wanted
to play the guitar.

321
00:27:58,218 --> 00:28:02,764
But when I saw Tania play the
violin, I also wanted to play it.

322
00:28:03,056 --> 00:28:05,767
♪

323
00:28:06,059 --> 00:28:08,896
We could try to practice Monday,
Wednesday and Saturday.

324
00:28:09,188 --> 00:28:12,816
Tania is emotionally closed off.

325
00:28:13,108 --> 00:28:16,445
We can practice
at María's house.

326
00:28:16,737 --> 00:28:23,660
When we ask her about her
life, she won't tell us anything.

327
00:28:23,952 --> 00:28:30,375
♪

328
00:28:30,667 --> 00:28:34,880
My best friend is María
because she's a good person.

329
00:28:35,172 --> 00:28:38,091
And she is able to keep secrets.

330
00:28:38,383 --> 00:28:40,052
♪

331
00:28:40,344 --> 00:28:43,889
If Tania is around a lot of new
people, she can be very shy.

332
00:28:44,181 --> 00:28:47,768
But once she gets to know
you, she will be your friend.

333
00:28:48,060 --> 00:28:52,898
She's your ally. She's
always looking out for you.

334
00:28:53,190 --> 00:28:55,734
She's a great friend.

335
00:28:56,026 --> 00:28:59,571
(singing melody)

336
00:29:06,745 --> 00:29:07,913
(laughing)

337
00:29:16,922 --> 00:29:22,135
How many girls do we
have? Four? No. There are six.

338
00:29:22,427 --> 00:29:26,014
Remember, these
shirts are for the concert.

339
00:29:33,563 --> 00:29:35,399
What do you think of
this color? Opinions?

340
00:29:37,317 --> 00:29:39,278
Alright. We're done
here. Thank you.

341
00:29:39,569 --> 00:29:41,196
Let's go.

342
00:29:41,488 --> 00:29:48,620
♪

343
00:29:48,912 --> 00:29:52,165
This is the first time that
I will fly in an airplane.

344
00:29:52,457 --> 00:29:54,334
It will be my first
time in a hotel.

345
00:29:54,626 --> 00:29:58,088
And it will also be my
first time seeing the ocean.

346
00:29:58,380 --> 00:30:06,305
But the most exciting part is to see a
new country, and be with my friends.

347
00:30:06,596 --> 00:30:09,099
I think all of the clothes
I own will fit in here.

348
00:30:09,391 --> 00:30:12,769
Let me know if you like these.
Speak now or forever hold your peace.

349
00:30:13,061 --> 00:30:18,608
You can't give them to me each
for 450 guaraní? No discount at all?

350
00:30:18,900 --> 00:30:20,319
- 480 each, right?
- Yes.

351
00:30:20,610 --> 00:30:22,529
Alright, let's go. Thank
you sir. See you later.

352
00:30:22,821 --> 00:30:28,535
♪

353
00:30:33,915 --> 00:30:36,475
One time María was practicing
violin and left her bow in the bed.

354
00:30:36,585 --> 00:30:38,754
And when I went
to bed I broke it.

355
00:30:39,046 --> 00:30:40,130
(laughing)

356
00:30:42,966 --> 00:30:47,346
What is the gesture that Estéban
always uses? Something like this...

357
00:30:47,637 --> 00:30:50,098
Favio understands your unique
language and gestures, right?

358
00:30:50,390 --> 00:30:53,643
I think he's almost ready
to publish a new dictionary...

359
00:30:53,935 --> 00:30:55,896
Spanish - Estéban,
Estéban - Spanish.

360
00:30:56,188 --> 00:30:58,148
Favio will ask him, " Is
your drum kit ready yet?"

361
00:30:58,273 --> 00:31:00,817
He responds, "Yes, I
just need to..." (gesture)

362
00:31:01,109 --> 00:31:06,114
What he is trying to say is " I
need to turn my kick drum around."

363
00:31:06,406 --> 00:31:08,200
(laughing)

364
00:31:09,534 --> 00:31:12,245
I have a hearing problem.

365
00:31:12,537 --> 00:31:16,041
When I was eight years
old I had the mumps.

366
00:31:16,333 --> 00:31:21,338
It's a disease that affected my
throat here, as well as my inner ear.

367
00:31:24,549 --> 00:31:27,886
He has always been
very hyperactive.

368
00:31:28,178 --> 00:31:31,139
He would play rhythms
on anything he could find.

369
00:31:31,431 --> 00:31:32,516
(tapping)

370
00:31:34,101 --> 00:31:36,770
It's something that
makes me feel free.

371
00:31:37,062 --> 00:31:38,438
It's my personality.

372
00:31:38,730 --> 00:31:41,066
Playing the drums liberates me.

373
00:31:41,358 --> 00:31:48,073
♪

374
00:31:48,365 --> 00:31:55,705
We took him to a doctor and he
said he could no longer play drums.

375
00:31:55,997 --> 00:32:01,628
He became very depressed by
this diagnosis. Very depressed.

376
00:32:01,920 --> 00:32:04,798
He didn't want to do anything.

377
00:32:05,090 --> 00:32:08,260
It was like they had stabbed
me with a sword right in the heart.

378
00:32:08,552 --> 00:32:10,432
They told me that I
needed to use a hearing aid.

379
00:32:10,512 --> 00:32:12,431
But I decided to keep
playing the drums.

380
00:32:12,722 --> 00:32:14,433
I don't want my
problem to hold me back.

381
00:32:14,724 --> 00:32:18,353
♪

382
00:32:18,645 --> 00:32:23,650
This is our last rehearsal
before our trip to Brazil.

383
00:32:23,942 --> 00:32:26,403
We're making sure all the
instruments are working correctly.

384
00:32:26,695 --> 00:32:28,738
There is still a
lot of work to do.

385
00:32:29,030 --> 00:32:33,535
Before a big event, I
always have trouble sleeping.

386
00:32:33,827 --> 00:32:36,163
Or I have nightmares that
I forget to do something.

387
00:32:36,455 --> 00:32:38,175
Or that there's some
kind of major problem.

388
00:32:38,457 --> 00:32:42,210
I never have enough time to anticipate
all of the challenges that will arise.

389
00:32:42,502 --> 00:32:44,622
I need to double-check all
of the children's documents

390
00:32:44,880 --> 00:32:46,923
to make sure they
are all good to travel.

391
00:32:47,215 --> 00:32:48,592
All of the violins
- play an "A."

392
00:32:48,884 --> 00:32:53,472
♪

393
00:32:53,763 --> 00:32:56,475
Alright. Let's try it
this time but with effort.

394
00:32:56,766 --> 00:33:04,766
♪

395
00:33:13,950 --> 00:33:16,703
First of all, you all are
fighting with the notes.

396
00:33:16,995 --> 00:33:17,995
♪

397
00:33:18,079 --> 00:33:25,295
Each note should sound crisp.
But your notes sound muddy.

398
00:33:25,587 --> 00:33:29,299
You're tripping over the notes.

399
00:33:30,675 --> 00:33:35,555
We have been invited to perform,
and there are high expectations of us.

400
00:33:35,847 --> 00:33:40,477
I know we're not big
stars like other groups.

401
00:33:40,769 --> 00:33:43,647
But we still have to
give it our best shot.

402
00:33:50,612 --> 00:33:52,572
This screw is totally stripped.

403
00:33:54,157 --> 00:33:57,202
To be a musician in
the Recycled Orchestra,

404
00:33:57,494 --> 00:34:01,456
you not only have to learn to play
music with these particular instruments,

405
00:34:01,748 --> 00:34:07,921
but you also need to solve the
problems that the instruments always have.

406
00:34:15,762 --> 00:34:19,766
Thus, each member of the orchestra
is both a musician and a luthier.

407
00:34:20,058 --> 00:34:23,728
I'm going to remove the
dents from this instrument.

408
00:34:24,020 --> 00:34:26,523
It needs to be more round,
as close to a circle as possible.

409
00:34:26,815 --> 00:34:29,734
Give it a try with the car jack.

410
00:34:31,111 --> 00:34:32,654
Give it two more turns.

411
00:34:32,946 --> 00:34:35,240
(clanking)

412
00:34:39,286 --> 00:34:40,495
Alright, that's good.

413
00:34:50,880 --> 00:34:52,632
No, I don't want any right now.

414
00:34:54,175 --> 00:35:02,175
Without music, my life
would be meaningless.

415
00:35:05,604 --> 00:35:07,814
♪

416
00:35:08,106 --> 00:35:11,192
Here in Paraguay, there is
a very important document

417
00:35:11,484 --> 00:35:13,862
that children need
in order to travel.

418
00:35:14,154 --> 00:35:17,157
Their parents must go to a court

419
00:35:17,449 --> 00:35:18,533
to sign a document

420
00:35:18,825 --> 00:35:21,012
that authorizes their children
to travel to other countries.

421
00:35:21,036 --> 00:35:23,079
♪

422
00:35:23,371 --> 00:35:26,207
I'm on the way to
find Tania's father

423
00:35:26,499 --> 00:35:32,255
because he needs to sign the authorization
for Tania to travel to Brazil.

424
00:35:32,547 --> 00:35:36,301
♪

425
00:35:36,593 --> 00:35:39,888
Tania's father told me
that if I didn't look for him,

426
00:35:40,180 --> 00:35:42,932
then he would not guarantee that
he would show up to sign the papers.

427
00:35:43,224 --> 00:35:44,601
♪

428
00:35:44,893 --> 00:35:48,355
Today is the day that the kids'
parents have to sign the paperwork

429
00:35:48,647 --> 00:35:51,941
because the judge has to meet
with us today, at this very moment.

430
00:35:52,233 --> 00:35:55,393
If Tania's father doesn't show up, then
Tania won't be able to travel to Brazil.

431
00:35:55,654 --> 00:35:57,656
♪

432
00:35:57,947 --> 00:36:01,368
I don't remember the
last time I saw my dad.

433
00:36:01,660 --> 00:36:04,913
♪

434
00:36:05,205 --> 00:36:06,925
Things were very
rough with Tania's father.

435
00:36:07,123 --> 00:36:11,920
He was very violent with us. He drinks
a lot. And I couldn't take it anymore.

436
00:36:12,212 --> 00:36:13,212
♪

437
00:36:13,380 --> 00:36:17,342
That must be
very difficult, Tania.

438
00:36:17,634 --> 00:36:24,224
♪

439
00:36:24,516 --> 00:36:29,145
From what I've heard, it's hard for
children who grow up with that situation

440
00:36:29,437 --> 00:36:32,399
to turn out okay in the end.

441
00:36:32,691 --> 00:36:34,109
Is he in the landfill already?

442
00:36:34,401 --> 00:36:36,069
I don't know. You'll
have to go check.

443
00:36:36,361 --> 00:36:37,779
Go ask his boss.

444
00:36:38,071 --> 00:36:41,574
I'm just going to stand by
the entrance to the landfill.

445
00:36:41,866 --> 00:36:45,286
I'll just be here a second
and then I'll leave for town.

446
00:36:45,578 --> 00:36:48,832
♪

447
00:36:49,124 --> 00:36:50,166
We'll be right there.

448
00:36:50,458 --> 00:36:52,353
They told me I had
permission to enter the landfill.

449
00:36:52,377 --> 00:36:55,171
I can't find Eugenio.

450
00:36:55,463 --> 00:36:57,549
♪

451
00:36:57,841 --> 00:36:59,121
I'll make a call over the radio.

452
00:36:59,175 --> 00:37:01,845
Find out if he's over
there in the landfill.

453
00:37:02,137 --> 00:37:10,137
♪

454
00:37:22,240 --> 00:37:24,826
- Hi.
- I waited for you.

455
00:37:25,118 --> 00:37:27,078
- When?
- Yesterday.

456
00:37:27,370 --> 00:37:30,582
No, I told you to be here today.

457
00:37:30,874 --> 00:37:38,874
♪

458
00:37:40,633 --> 00:37:41,968
Come over here, Eugenio.

459
00:37:44,304 --> 00:37:45,584
Sir, your identification please.

460
00:37:45,847 --> 00:37:47,407
And the identification
of the children.

461
00:37:49,017 --> 00:37:50,732
It's more difficult
working with the

462
00:37:50,744 --> 00:37:52,854
parents than it is with
the kids in Cateura.

463
00:37:54,314 --> 00:37:55,482
Your address, sir?

464
00:38:05,742 --> 00:38:08,745
- Sonia Jazmín? Sonia?
- Tania. Tania.

465
00:38:09,037 --> 00:38:11,539
- Tania, right.
- Do you have your ID card?

466
00:38:11,831 --> 00:38:13,666
Go to the fourth window.

467
00:38:13,958 --> 00:38:21,958
♪

468
00:38:40,568 --> 00:38:41,568
What's up, mom?

469
00:38:41,820 --> 00:38:43,988
Do you have everything ready?

470
00:38:44,280 --> 00:38:45,640
What else are you
taking with you?

471
00:38:45,698 --> 00:38:48,868
♪

472
00:38:49,160 --> 00:38:52,288
I've put too many clothes
in here. Nothing else will fit.

473
00:38:52,580 --> 00:39:00,580
♪

474
00:39:03,466 --> 00:39:05,677
(announcer on TV)

475
00:39:05,969 --> 00:39:13,059
♪

476
00:39:13,351 --> 00:39:18,982
When the plan takes off,
it's going to shake a lot.

477
00:39:19,274 --> 00:39:20,316
♪

478
00:39:20,608 --> 00:39:21,693
(laughing)

479
00:39:21,985 --> 00:39:26,072
But that's normal. And
it's only for a moment.

480
00:39:26,364 --> 00:39:27,949
Would you like to go, Dad?

481
00:39:28,241 --> 00:39:30,201
Yeah, I'd like to go see
the Brazilian women.

482
00:39:30,493 --> 00:39:35,665
♪

483
00:39:35,957 --> 00:39:37,917
Bye, Dad.

484
00:39:38,209 --> 00:39:46,209
♪

485
00:39:59,272 --> 00:40:01,149
Finally.

486
00:40:01,441 --> 00:40:09,441
♪

487
00:40:30,386 --> 00:40:32,055
Nati, where is your side locker?

488
00:40:32,347 --> 00:40:35,141
It's number 5.

489
00:40:35,433 --> 00:40:38,311
If you need soap, the woman at the
front desk said that they have some.

490
00:40:41,981 --> 00:40:43,816
Wow. Check this out.

491
00:40:44,108 --> 00:40:46,736
Come over here and
sit with me in the window.

492
00:40:48,196 --> 00:40:49,197
Five more minutes.

493
00:40:54,661 --> 00:40:58,414
The anxiety I feel
is overwhelming.

494
00:40:58,706 --> 00:41:03,211
I have goosebumps.
I'm excited and nervous.

495
00:41:09,842 --> 00:41:12,261
(announcement over loudspeaker)

496
00:41:23,064 --> 00:41:26,192
Look, don't be nervous. There
are going to be a lot of people here.

497
00:41:26,484 --> 00:41:28,653
Be sure to smile.

498
00:41:28,945 --> 00:41:34,409
The only moments when you need to
be serious are when we finish a song

499
00:41:34,701 --> 00:41:36,661
and we're about to
begin the next one.

500
00:41:36,953 --> 00:41:38,753
Because we don't know
what's going to happen.

501
00:41:38,913 --> 00:41:40,891
I still don't know the order of
the songs we're going to play.

502
00:41:40,915 --> 00:41:45,920
But this is a great opportunity to show
off the orchestra and represent Paraguay.

503
00:41:46,212 --> 00:41:50,174
How does that sound?
Everyone excited?

504
00:41:50,466 --> 00:41:51,926
(applause)

505
00:41:52,218 --> 00:41:54,220
We play all types of music.

506
00:41:54,512 --> 00:42:01,811
For example, we play classical
music that you've probably heard before.

507
00:42:02,103 --> 00:42:07,150
But I'm sure you've never heard
Mozart played with garbage.

508
00:42:07,442 --> 00:42:15,442
♪

509
00:42:44,270 --> 00:42:46,606
(applause)

510
00:42:49,358 --> 00:42:57,358
♪

511
00:43:13,758 --> 00:43:15,885
(laughs)

512
00:43:16,177 --> 00:43:24,177
♪

513
00:43:34,904 --> 00:43:40,284
We're going to the beach!
We're going to the beach!

514
00:43:40,576 --> 00:43:48,576
♪

515
00:44:57,445 --> 00:44:59,822
(roosters crowing)

516
